y seem to place league table results above the aspirations of students - despite him asking to be put in for higher tier GCSE maths papers, his school seems intent on playing it safe to bulk up their pass rate. &#10;The best advice I could give to people is to become very involved in their child's education - my brother thanked me once for the advice about the GCSE papers and he actively wants to improve his qualifications at college rather than accept the substandard education his secondary school is happy to leave him with for the sake of league tables. State schools are failing a lot of pupils, not just black boys. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="929" language="en" documentId="822" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="MostUncivilised" date="07 January 2011 4:03pm" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://discussion.theguardian.com/comment-permalink/9055544" topic="homeschooling" thumbsUp="3" thumbsDown="0" origId="822" notes="" title="Why I home school my children"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="518"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="519" end="929"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43"/></xmi:XMI>